{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.2,0.46,0.11,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66633"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9420"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52086"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4719"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11990"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43648"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66633"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for contraceptive advice. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is in a monogamous relationship and is interested in non-hormonal contraceptive options. She has regular menstrual cycles and no history of abnormal cervical screening. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. After discussion of various options, she decides to try a diaphragm for contraception.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding timing of diaphragm removal?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Remove at next menstruation","Remove immediately after intercourse","Remove 6 hours after intercourse","Remove 2 hours after intercourse","Remove 36 hours after intercourse"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe diaphragm is a barrier method of contraception that works by preventing sperm from entering the cervix. When used correctly with spermicide, it has a failure rate of approximately 12% with typical use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoving 6 hours after intercourse\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct advice. This time period is necessary to ensure that any sperm present in the vagina are no longer viable, thus maintaining contraceptive effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoving immediately after intercourse\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E2 hours after intercourse\u003C/strong\u003E would significantly reduce the contraceptive effectiveness as viable sperm may still be present in the vagina and could reach the cervix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoving 36 hours after intercourse\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as leaving a diaphragm in place for more than 24 hours increases the risk of toxic shock syndrome and vaginal infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoving at next menstruation\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous as it could lead to toxic shock syndrome. The diaphragm should be removed, cleaned, and stored after the recommended 6-24 hour period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional important counselling points include: inserting the diaphragm up to 6 hours before intercourse, using additional spermicide for each act of intercourse, and ensuring proper fit through regular checks with a healthcare provider.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A diaphragm must remain in place for at least 6 hours after intercourse to ensure contraceptive effectiveness.","Diaphragms should not be left in place for longer than 24 hours due to risk of toxic shock syndrome.","Spermicide must be reapplied before each act of intercourse when using a diaphragm."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Contraception: Clinical Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Contraception-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52086"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52086"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T17:35:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T17:36:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9420"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66633"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"